{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/how-to-create-a-race-bar-animated-plot-in-a-single-long-piped-r-line-of-code-6216f09ed844", "time": 1683015720.183327, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/how-to-create-a-race-bar-animated-plot-in-a-single-long-piped-r-line-of-code-6216f09ed844/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "How to create a race bar animated plot in a single-long-piped R line of code | by Dror Berel | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How to create a race bar animated plot in a single-long-piped R line of code", "description": "When you want to shoot an impressive complex falling domino tiles video, are you going to take the risk of accidentally flip one cube before it is completed, and ruin the whole thing, or would you\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/magrittr/vignettes/magrittr.htmlhttps://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/magrittr/vignettes/magrittr.html", "anchor_text": "magrittr", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/covid-19-open-data", "anchor_text": "Covid-19 Open data project", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://github.com/drorberel/mediumHTML/blob/main/race2.html", "anchor_text": "HTML animation file", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://drorberel.medium.com/covid-19-death-visualization-race-bar-chart-for-us-states-96edc59102a9", "anchor_text": "earlier post of mine", "paragraph_index": 9}], "all_paragraphs": ["Long piped R commands\u2026 Some loves it, and some don\u2019t!", "When you want to shoot an impressive complex falling domino tiles video, are you going to take the risk of accidentally flip one cube before it is completed, and ruin the whole thing, or would you prefer break it into independent units, better isolated, that would also allow you to explore, and test its features, without harming the other parts?", "In case of R, the pipe operator, originally from the package magrittr, allows you to pass along an object to the next function. So technically you can keep passing along objects into other functions without breaking the chain, or by avoiding less readable nested functions.", "Just like in the domino analogy above, I don\u2019t think there is a rule, and it should be self guided based on how comfortable you are with the use of pipes, and other limitation you might have such as connection to external source of the data frame (or other input parameters), computational memory etc.", "Breaking the chain is recommended mostly for readability, and documentation, but in terms of performance, may not be required. It is like reading a long order of steps (functions) in a single long sentence, without stopping for re-breath.", "In the following example, for the sake of demonstration, I created a single long piped R line of code, that can be run in one shot. Again, probably not the most recommended style, but made it worth the effort for the catchy title, and practice of the nested-pipe use with the {}.", "I used COVID-19 cumulative number of deaths, by US state, from the Covid-19 Open data project.", "The above code will create the animation, saved in HTML file format.", "HTML animation file can be found at my GitHub repo. Below a recorded video from my screen, therefore the degraded quality.", "This blog post is very similar to an earlier post of mine (hurray, cross self-referencing) with COVID-19 related title that I posted a day before this one. The reason for the similar posts, though with different emphasis, is to test how much of \u2018audience attention\u2019 (claps, views) each will attract. Of course, each post is promoted differently: published under an aggregator publication, LinkedIn, Facebook, Twitter, R-bloggers, timing of day-of-launch effect, and others. Will be glad to share my findings later on.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "BioPassenger, Computational Biology for the people"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24ca